{{Infobox NRHP | name = Monadnock Building | image = Monadnock.jpg | image_size = 220px | caption = Building seen from Dearborn Street in 2005. The north half is in the foreground. | architectural_style = [[Chicago school (architecture)|Chicago School]] | location = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], US | locmapin = United States Chicago Loop | map_width = 220 | map_caption = Location in [[Chicago Loop]] | lat_degrees = 41 | lat_minutes = 52 | lat_seconds = 39 | lat_direction = N | long_degrees = 87 | long_minutes = 37 | long_seconds = 46 | long_direction = W | coord_parameters = region:US-IL_type:landmark | coord_display = title | architect = [[Burnham & Root]] and [[Holabird & Roche]] | built = 1891–{{Start date|1893}} | nrhp_type = nhldcp | nocat = yes | partof = [[Printing House Row District|South Dearborn Street – Printing House Row North Historic District]]{{sfn|National Park Service|1976}} | partof_refnum = 76000705 | designated_other1_name = Chicago Landmark | designated_other1_date = November 14, 1973{{sfn|City of Chicago|1973}} | designated_other1_abbr = CL | designated_other1_link = Chicago Landmark | designated_other1_color = #aaccff | added = November 20, 1970{{sfn|National Park Service|1970}} | refnum = 70000236 }}
The '''Monadnock Building''' (historically the '''Monadnock Block'''; pronounced {{IPAc-en|m|ə|ˈ|n|æ|d|n|ɒ|k}} {{respell|mə|NAD|nok}}) is a [[skyscraper]] located at 53 West Jackson Boulevard in the south [[Chicago Loop|Loop]] area of [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]. The north half of the building was designed by the firm of [[Burnham & Root]] and built starting in 1891. The tallest [[load-bearing wall|load-bearing]] brick building ever constructed, it employed the first portal system of wind bracing in America. Its decorative staircases represent the first structural use of aluminum in building construction. The south half, constructed in 1893, was designed by [[Holabird & Roche]] and is similar in color and profile to the original, but the design is more traditionally ornate. When completed, it was the largest office building in the world. The success of the building was the catalyst for an important new business center at the southern end of the Loop.
The building was remodeled in 1938 in one of the first major skyscraper renovations ever undertaken—a bid, in part, to revolutionize how building maintenance was done and halt the demolition of [[Architecture of Chicago#Skyscrapers|Chicago's aging skyscrapers]]. It was sold in 1979 to owners who restored the building to its original condition, in one of the most comprehensive skyscraper restorations attempted as of 1992. The project was recognized as one of the top restoration projects in the USA by the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]] in 1987. The building is divided into offices from {{convert|250|sqft}} to {{convert|6000|sqft}} in size, and primarily serves independent professional firms. It was listed for sale in 2007.
The north half is an unornamented vertical mass of purple-brown brick, flaring gently out at the base and top, with vertically continuous bay windows projecting out. The south half is vertically divided by brickwork at the base and rises to a large copper [[cornice]] at the roof. Projecting window [[bay (architecture)|bay]]s in both halves allow large exposures of glass, giving the building an open appearance despite its mass. The Monadnock is part of the [[Printing House Row District]], which also includes the [[Fisher Building (Chicago)|Fisher Building]], the [[Manhattan Building (Chicago, Illinois)|Manhattan Building]], and the [[Old Colony Building (Chicago)|Old Colony Building]].
When it was built, many critics called the building too extreme, and lacking in style. Others found in its lack of ornamentation the natural extension of its commercial purpose and an expression of modern business life. Early 20th-century European architects found inspiration in its attention to purpose and functional expression. It was one of the first buildings named a [[Chicago Landmark|Chicago Architectural Landmark]] in 1958. It was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1970, and named as part of the [[National Historic Landmark]] South Dearborn Street – Printing House Row North Historic District in 1976. Modern critics have called it a "classic", a "triumph of unified design", and "one of the most exciting aesthetic experiences America's commercial architecture produced".{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=8}}
== History ==
=== North half (1881–1891) ===
The Monadnock was commissioned by Boston real estate developers Peter and Shepherd Brooks in the building boom following the [[Long Depression|Depression of 1873–79]].{{sfn|Miller|1997|p=320}} The Brooks family, which had amassed a fortune in the shipping insurance business and had been investing in Chicago real estate since 1863, had retained Chicago property manager [[Owen F. Aldis]] to manage the construction of the seven-story [[Grannis Block]] on Dearborn Street in 1880.{{sfn|Berger|1992|p=34}} It was Aldis, one of two men [[Louis Sullivan]] credited with being "responsible for the modern office building",{{sfn|Miller|1997|p=319}}{{efn|name=a}} who convinced investors such as the Brooks brothers to build new skyscrapers in Chicago. By the end of the century, Aldis would create over {{convert|1000000|sqft}} of new office space and manage nearly one fifth of the office space in the Loop.{{sfn|Douglas|2004|p=19}}{{sfn|Berger|1992|p=39}}
[[Daniel Burnham]] and [[John Wellborn Root]] met as young draftsmen in the Chicago firm of Carter, Drake, and Wight in 1872 and left to form [[Burnham & Root]] the following year.{{sfn|Hines|2008|p=17}} At Aldis's urging, the Brooks brothers had retained the then-fledgling firm to design the Grannis Block, which was their first major commission.{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=18}} Burnham and Root would become the architects of choice for the Brooks family, for whom they would complete the first high-rise building in Chicago, the 10-story [[Montauk Building]], in 1883, and the 11-story [[Rookery Building]] in 1888.{{sfn|Miller|1997|pp=319, 326}}
{{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | header = | header_align = left/right/center | header_background = | footer = | footer_align = left/right/center | footer_background = | width = | image1 = Jackson Street Elevation 1885.jpg | width1 = 120 | caption1 = 1885 sketch of preliminary design showing a smaller, more ornate building with [[Egyptian revival|Egyptian]]-style detailing | alt1 = | image2 = Monadnock Sketch 1889.jpg | width2 = 168 | caption2 = Sketch of vastly simplified 1889 design, abolishing ornamentation entirely in favor of plain contoured brick | alt2 = }}
The [[Great Chicago Fire]] of 1871 had destroyed a {{convert|4|mi|adj=on}} by {{convert|0.5|mi|adj=on}} swath of the city between the Chicago River and [[Lake Michigan]], and subsequent commercial development expanded into the area far south of the main business district along the river that would come to be known as [[Chicago Loop|"the Loop"]].{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=16}} Between 1881 and 1885, Aldis bought a series of lots in the area on Peter Brooks' behalf, including a 70-by-200-foot (21 by 61 m) site on the corner of Jackson and Dearborn streets.{{sfn|Berger|1992|p=44}} The location was remote, yet attractive for several reasons. The construction of the [[Chicago Board of Trade Building]] in 1885 had made nearby [[LaSalle Street]] the city's prime financial district, driving up property values, and railroad companies were buying up land further south for new terminal buildings, creating further speculation in the southeastern end of the Loop.{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|pp=20,58}} Brooks commissioned Burnham & Root to design a building for the site in 1884, and the project was announced in 1885, with a brief trade journal notice that the building would cost $850,000 (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|850000|1885}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars).{{sfn|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis}}{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=58}} The Chicago building community had little faith in Brooks' choice of location. Architect Edwin Renwick would say: {{quote|When Owen Aldis put up the Monadnock on Jackson Boulevard there was nothing on the south side of the street between State Street and the river but cheap one-story shacks, mere hovels. Every one thought Mr. Aldis was insane to build way out there on the ragged edge of the city. Later when he carried the building on through Van Buren Street they were sure he was.{{sfn|Randall|1999|p=141}}}}
Early sketches show a 13-story building with [[Ancient Egyptian architecture|Ancient Egyptian]] ornament and a slight flaring at the top, divided visually into five sections with a [[lotus flower|lotus-blossom]] decorative [[motif (visual arts)|motif]]. This design was never approved, as Brooks waited for the real estate market in the south Loop, still mostly warehouses, to improve.{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=58}} Where Root was known for the detailed ornamentation of his designs (as seen in the [[Rookery Building]]), Brooks was known for his stinginess and preference for simplicity. For the Monadnock, Brooks insisted that the architects refrain from elaborate ornamentation and produce instead "the effect of solidity and strength, or a design that will produce that effect, rather than ornament for a notable appearance."{{sfn|Hoffman|1973|p=156}} In an 1884 letter to Aldis, he wrote: {{quote|My notion is to have no projecting surfaces or indentations, but to have everything flush&nbsp;.... So tall and narrow a building must have some ornament in so conspicuous a situation&nbsp;... [but] projections mean dirt, nor do they add strength to the building&nbsp;... one great nuisance [is] the lodgment of pigeons and sparrows.{{sfn|Commission on Chicago Historical and Architectural Landmarks|1976|p=3}}}} While Root was on vacation, Burnham had a draftsman create a "straight up-and-down, uncompromising, unornamented [[facade]]."{{sfn|Condit|1973|p=66}} Objecting at first, Root later threw himself into the design, declaring that the heavy lines of an Egyptian pyramid had captured his imagination and that he would "throw the thing up without a single ornament".{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=58}}{{sfn|Condit|1973|p=67}}
In 1889, a new plan was announced for the building: a thick-walled brick tower, 16 stories high, devoid of ornamentation and suggestive of an Egyptian [[Pylon (architecture)|pylon]].{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=58}}{{sfn|Sinkevitch|2004|pp=63–64}} Brooks insisted that the building have no projections, for which reason the plan did not include [[bay window]]s, but Aldis argued that more rentable space would be created by projecting [[oriel window]]s, which were included in the final design.{{sfn|Commission on Chicago Historical and Architectural Landmarks|1972|p=8}} The Monadnock's final height was calculated to be the highest economically viable for a [[load-bearing wall]] design, requiring walls {{convert|6|ft}} thick at the bottom and {{convert|18|in|cm}} thick at the top. Greater height would have required walls of such thickness that they would have reduced the rentable space too greatly. The final height was much dithered over by the owners, but a decision was forced when the city proposed an ordinance restricting the height of buildings to {{convert|150|ft}}.{{sfn|''American Architect''|1892|p=134}} To protect future income potential, Aldis sought a permit for a 16-story building immediately. The building commissioner, although "staggered by the sixteen story plan",{{sfn|Commission on Chicago Historical and Architectural Landmarks|1972|p=8}} granted the permit on June 3, 1889.{{sfn|Commission on Chicago Historical and Architectural Landmarks|1972|p=8}}
[[File:Monadnock Aluminum Staircase 1893.JPG|thumb|upright|left|The decorative cast aluminum staircases, shown here in 1893, were the first use of aluminum in building construction.]]
With its 17 stories (16 rentable plus an attic), its {{convert|215|ft}} high load-bearing walls were the tallest of any commercial structure in the world.{{sfn|Fuller|1958|p=B5}}{{efn|name=b}} To support the towering structure and reinforce against wind, the masonry walls were braced with an interior frame of [[cast iron|cast]] and [[wrought iron]]. Root devised for this frame the first attempt at a portal system of [[wind brace|wind bracing]] in America, in which iron [[strut]]s were riveted between the columns of the frame for reinforcement.{{sfn|Condit|1973|p=67}}{{efn|name=c}} The narrow lot allowed only a single, double-loaded corridor, which was appointed with a {{convert|3|ft|adj=on}} high [[Panelling|wainscot]] of white [[Carrara]] marble, red oak trim, and feather-chipped glass{{efn|name=d}} that allowed outside light to filter from the offices on each side into the hallways. Floors were covered with hand-carved marble [[mosaic]] tiles.{{sfn|Miller|1991|p=147}} [[Skylight (window)|Skylit]] open staircases were made of bronze-plated cast iron on upper floors.{{sfn|Keohan|1989|p=6}} On the ground floor, they were crafted in cast aluminum—an exotic and expensive material at the time—representing the first use of aluminum in building construction.{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=58}}{{sfn|National Park Service|1992|p=85}}{{efn|name=e}}
The building was constructed by the firm of [[George A. Fuller]], who trained as an architect but made his mark as the creator of the modern [[general contractor|contracting]] system in building construction. His firm had supervised construction of the Rookery, and later built New York's [[Flatiron Building]] with Burnham in 1902.{{sfn|Overby|Homolka|1963|p=2}}{{sfn|Sinkevitch|2004|p=469}} The Monadnock Block was built as a single structure but was legally two buildings, the Monadnock and the Kearsarge, named for [[Mount Monadnock]] and [[Mount Kearsarge (Merrimack County, New Hampshire)|Mount Kearsarge]] in New Hampshire.{{efn|name=f}} Work was completed in 1891. The Monadnock, which Root called his "Jumbo", was his last project; he died suddenly while it was under construction.{{sfn|Monroe|1896|p=141}}{{sfn|Hoffman|1973|p=155}}
{{clear}}
=== South half and early history (1891–1893) ===
[[File:MONADNOCK BUILDING AERIAL 1910.jpg|left|thumb|upright|1910 postcard of south half of the Monadnock, showing the [[arcade (architecture)|arcade]]-like treatment of the upper floors and neoclassical copper [[cornice]]]]
Encouraged by the early success of the building, Shepherd Brooks purchased the 68-by-200-foot (21 by 61 m) lot adjoining to the south in 1893 for $360,000 (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|360000|1893}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars).{{sfn|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis}}{{sfn|Plumbe|1893|p=383}} Aldis recommended the firm of [[Holabird & Roche]], who had designed the [[Pontiac Building]] for Peter Brooks in 1891, to extend the Monadnock south to Van Buren.{{sfn|''Chicago Daily Tribune''|April 1893|p=30}}{{sfn|Clarke|Saliga|Zukowsky|1990|pp=41–42}} [[William Holabird]] and [[Martin Roche]] had trained together in the office of [[William LeBaron Jenney]], and in 1881 formed their own firm, which would become one of the most prolific in the city and the acknowledged leader of the [[Chicago school (architecture)|Chicago school]] of architecture.{{efn|name=g}} The north half had struggled with cost overruns and Holabird & Roche presented a far more cost-effective design.{{sfn|Hoffman|1973|p=165}} The design, for two buildings called the [[Mount Katahdin|Katahdin]] and [[Mount Wachusett|Wachusett]] (also named for [[New England]] mountains), connected them to the north half as a single structure at an estimated cost of $800,000 (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|800000|1893}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars).{{sfn|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis}}{{sfn|Commission on Chicago Historical and Architectural Landmarks|1972|p=3}}{{sfn|''Chicago Daily Tribune''|January 1893|p=28}} Construction began in 1892, under the supervision of [[Corydon T. Purdy]] who would later earn accolades as the structural engineer for many famous Chicago and New York skyscrapers.{{sfn|Condit|1973|p=119}}
The addition, 17 stories high, preserved the color and vertically massed profile of the original, but was more traditionally ornate in its design, with grander entranceways and more [[neoclassical architecture|neoclassical]] touches.{{sfn|Commission on Chicago Historical and Architectural Landmarks|1972|p=4}} The building reflected in its design the transition taking place in skyscraper design from load-bearing walls to steel frame construction .{{sfn|Fuller|1958|p=B5}} The Katahdin, built first, used the same iron framed masonry construction as the original. The Wachusett was entirely [[steel frame]]d.{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=60}} Where the north half required great thicknesses of brick in the load-bearing walls, the addition employed only a thin facing of brick and [[terracotta]] trim, affording larger expanses of glass and faster, less expensive construction.{{sfn|Commission on Chicago Historical and Architectural Landmarks|1972|p=4}} The south half cost 15&nbsp;percent less, weighed 15&nbsp;percent less, and had 15&nbsp;percent more rentable space than the north half.{{sfn|Bruegmann|1997|p=472}} Connected on every floor except the top one and sharing a common basement, each of the four component buildings was equipped with its own heating system, elevators, stairs, and plumbing to facilitate a separate sale if required.{{sfn|Fuller|1958|p=B5}} The combined final cost in 1893 was $2.5 million (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|2500000|1893}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars).{{sfn|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis}}{{sfn|Rand McNally|1898|p=24}}
When complete, the Monadnock was the largest office building in the world, with 1,200 rooms and an occupancy of over 6,000.{{sfn|Kerch|1991}} The ''[[Chicago Daily Tribune]]'' commented that the population of most Illinois towns in 1896 would fit comfortably in the building.{{sfn|Plumbe|1893|p=3}}{{sfn|''Chicago Daily Tribune''|1896|p=3}} It was a postal district unto itself, with four full-time carriers delivering mail six times a day, six days a week.{{sfn|''Chicago Daily Tribune''|1900|p=49}} It was the first building in Chicago wired for electricity, and one of the first to be fire-proofed, with hollow [[fire clay]] tiles lining the structure so that the metal frame would be protected even if the facing brick were to be destroyed.{{sfn|Plumbe|1893|p=383}}{{sfn|Keohan|1989|p=1}}
[[File:Adams Street Looking South 1898.JPG|thumb|Bird's-eye view of the southeast Loop, looking south from Adams street, in 1898. The completed Monadnock (7) is to the top right. Rand McNally called these buildings "some of the most remarkable buildings in the world".{{sfn|Rand McNally|1898|p=22}}]] The Brooks' decision to construct a building of such scale and in such an unlikely location was vindicated by the Monadnock's success—it was the most profitable investment they ever made.{{sfn|Condit|1973|p=66}} ''The Economist,'' a Chicago real estate journal, conceded in 1892 that:
{{quote | the rapidity with which the Monadnock and Kearsarge ... have been rented is one of the phenomenal features in the real estate market of this city. The erecting and successful renting of these structures has simply established, in an incredibly short period of time, an important business center at the southwest corner of Jackson and Dearborn streets, a point which was but a short time ago considered too far south for a prosperous business center.{{sfn|Berger|1992|p=45}} }}
Early tenants, according to [[Rand McNally]], included "great corporations, banks, and professional men ... among them the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway|Santa Fe]], the [[Michigan Central Railroad|Michigan Central]], and the [[Alton Railroad|Chicago & Alton]] Railroads, and the American Exchange National and Globe Savings Banks".{{sfn|Rand McNally|1898|p=24}}
In 1897, the [[Union Elevated Railroad]] Company opened the [[Union Loop]] line of the [[Chicago "L"]], the last leg of which ran immediately alongside the Van Buren side of the building.{{sfn|Borzo|2007|pp=54–55}}{{efn|name=h}} Aldis filed suit against the "L" in 1901 for $300,000 in damages (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|300000|1901}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars), complaining that:
{{quote | [the] means of access to the said building ... had been cut off and the light, air, and view obstructed, and the enjoyment of the property disturbed by the throwing of smoke, dust, cinders, and filth ... by the creating and causing of loud and ominous noises, and by the causing of the ground to shake and vibrate ... said building and premises are greatly damaged.{{sfn|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis}}{{sfn|''Chicago Daily Tribune''|1901|p=A5}}{{sfn|''Chicago Daily Tribune''|1903|p=8}} }}
Aldis lost the case, but won on appeal, when the Supreme Court of Illinois found that owners of property abutting the "L" lines could recover damages if the property had been injured by noise, vibration, or the blocking of light, paving the way for many lawsuits to follow.{{sfn|Aldis v. Union Elevated R. Co.|1903}}{{sfn|''New York Times''|1903}}
=== Modernization (1938–1979) ===
{{multiple image | align = left | direction = horizontal | header = | header_align = left/right/center | header_background = | footer = "Progressive styling" of older offices (left) into more modern [[art deco]] suites (right) in 1938 included replacing small partitioned spaces with larger offices and sheer plaster walls, and installing closets, cabinets, and radiator covers.{{sfn|Architectural Forum|1938|p=307}} | footer_align = left/right/center | footer_background = | width = | image1 = Monandock Remodel Before 1938 (2).JPG | width1 = 118 | caption1 = | alt1 = | image2 = Monandnock After Remodel 1938 (2).JPG | width2 = 120 | caption2 = | alt2 = }}
A boom in new construction after 1926 created stiff competition for older buildings like the Monadnock. Occupancy declined from 87&nbsp;percent in 1929 to 55&nbsp;percent in 1937 and the building began to lose money.{{sfn|Architectural Forum|1938|p=307}} In 1938, building manager Graham Aldis (Owen's nephew) announced what the ''Chicago Daily Tribune'' called "the city's largest and most novel modernization job"{{sfn|Chase|1938|p=C12}} in a move toward halting the destruction of Chicago's aging skyscrapers. Rejecting the term "modernization", Aldis called his plan "progressive styling", which he believed would revolutionize the way building maintenance was done to preserve millions of dollars worth of buildings that would otherwise be destroyed. "There is no reason why", he said, "any well-designed office building need be torn down because of obsolescence."{{sfn|Chase|1938|p=C12}} [[Skidmore, Owings and Merrill|Skidmore & Owings]], who had pioneered functional design, were retained to lead a $125,000 program (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|125000|1938}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars) to restyle the main entrance, remodel the lobby and ground floor shops, modernize all the public spaces, and progressively modernize office suites as demand required.{{sfn|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis}}{{sfn|Architectural Forum|1938|p=307}} The modernization included covering the mosaic floors with rubber tile and [[terrazzo]], enclosing the elevators and ornamental stairways, and replacing the marble and oak finishes in the corridors and offices with modern materials.{{sfn|Chase|1938|p=C12}} By the end of 1938, 35 new tenants had signed leases and 11 existing tenants had leased additional space in the building.{{sfn|''Chicago Daily Tribune''|1938|p=C14}}
In 1966, Aldis & Co., which had managed the building for the Brooks estate for 75&nbsp;years, was dissolved and the Monadnock was sold for $2&nbsp;million (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|2000000|1966}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars) to Sudler & Co., owners of the [[John Hancock Center]], the Rookery, and the [[Old Colony Building (Chicago)|Old Colony Building]].{{sfn|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis}}{{sfn|Nagelberg|1967|p=D3}}{{sfn|Nagelberg|1966|p=C5}} The new owners again modernized the interior, installing carpet, [[fluorescent lamp|fluorescent lights]], and new doors, and undertook a major effort to shore up the north wall which had sunk {{convert|1.75|in}} during construction of the [[Kluczynski Federal Building]] across Jackson Street in 1974.{{sfn|Nagelberg|1967|p=D3}}{{sfn|''Chicago Tribune''|1966|p=C5}}
By 1977, operating expenses were high, rents were low, and occupancy had fallen to 80&nbsp;percent.{{sfn|Storch|Branegan|1979|p=E7}}{{sfn|Washburn|1982|p=N_B1}} Struggling to make loan payments, the owners were forced to sell the building to avoid foreclosure.{{sfn|Storch|Branegan|1979|p=E7}}{{sfn|Washburn|1982|p=N_B1}} It was purchased by a partnership headed by William S. Donnell in 1979 for $5 per square foot ($53.82 per square meter) or approximately $2 million (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|2000000|1979}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars).{{sfn|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis}}{{sfn|''Chicago Tribune''|1979|p=E8}}{{sfn|Keohan|1989|p=5}}
{{clear}}
=== Restoration and later (1979–) ===
{{multiple image | align = right | direction = horizontal | header = | header_align = left/right/center | header_background = | footer = | footer_align = left/right/center | footer_background = | width = | image1 = Monadnock Corridor Before Rehab.JPG | width1 = 120 | caption1 = Prior to restoration, glass and oak partitions and marble [[panelling|wainscot]] had been removed and the ceilings were suspended. | alt1 = | image2 = Monandock Building Rehabbed Corridor.JPG | width2 = 142 | caption2 = Restored corridor showing marble wainscot, oak and chipped glass partitions, full ceiling height, and open ornamental stairs | alt2 = }}
The building Donnell purchased in 1979 had declined badly. The Dearborn entrances had been closed in, the ground floor had been "defaced by garish signs",{{sfn|Weese|1978|p=90}} and the brick had been painted and was peeling. Inside, the marble wainscoting had been painted over and many of the original oak doors had been replaced with cheaper mahogany. The decorative stair rails had been enclosed, and some stairways and corridors had been closed off completely. Much of the original mosaic tile had been demolished—some floors were carpeted, others tiled in [[vinyl]] or terrazzo. Half of the sixteen elevators were still manually operated.{{sfn|Weese|1978|p=90}} "It was as if it had been partly updated every ten years throughout its history", said Donnell, "it was never done over in its entirety."{{sfn|Washburn|1982|p=N_B1}}
Donnell, who had studied architecture at [[Harvard University|Harvard]], planned to gut the building and construct a new, modern office complex inside the historic shell. Failing to obtain financing for the remodeling, he embarked instead on an incremental, "pay as you go"{{sfn|Newman|1991}} project to restore the Monadnock to its original condition in painstaking detail.{{sfn|Miller|1991|p=147}} The project was, according to historian Donald Miller, the most comprehensive skyscraper restoration ever attempted at the time; it took thirteen years to complete.{{sfn|Miller|1991|pp=140–141}} Working from original drawings discovered at the [[Art Institute of Chicago]], and two old photographs, Donnell and [[John Vinci]], one of the nation's leading preservation architects, restored the building to its condition when first constructed, before any modernizations, working piecemeal as offices became vacant.{{sfn|''Chicago Tribune''|October 1987|p=2D}}{{sfn|Miller|1991|pp=145,147}}
{{multiple image | align = left | direction = horizontal | header_align = left/right/center | footer = Detail of replica ceiling fixture, [[mosaic]] tile, and wall fixture found in the retail lobby in 2010 | footer_align = left/right/center | width = | image1 = Monadnock Ceiling Lamp crop 2.jpg | width1 = 100 | caption1 = | alt1 = | image2 = Monadnock Mosaic Tile 2010.jpg | width2 = 100 | caption2 = | alt2 = | image3 = Monadnock Wall Fixture 2010.jpg | width3 = 100 }}
The color of the [[shellac]] was matched to closets where the wood had not been darkened by exposure to light. The mosaic floors were recreated by Italian craftsmen at a cost of $50 per square foot ($538.12 per square meter).{{sfn|Clarke|Saliga|Zukowsky|1990|pp=41–42}} A local firm was found that could reproduce the complicated process of [[abrasive blasting|sandblasting]] and [[animal glue|hide glue]] application used to create the original feather chipped glass. This reproduced glass was used to restore the partitions and naturally lit corridors of Root's design.{{sfn|Clarke|1985|p=22}} To recreate the doors and wood trim, Donnell purchased the firm that had created the original oak woodwork—and still used the same 19th century machinery.{{sfn|Washburn|1982|p=N_B1}} Perfect replicas of the original aluminum light fixtures were fabricated from early photographs and [[carbon filament]] light bulbs were obtained to recreate the original lighting effect.{{sfn|Miller|1991|p=145}} A single surviving aluminum staircase was discovered behind a wall, restored, and used as a model to rebuild the lobby stairways and metalwork.{{sfn|Clarke|1985|p=22}} The wainscoting on the upper floors was restored with marble salvaged from the recently modernized, nearby 19 LaSalle and [[Manhattan Building (Chicago, Illinois)|Manhattan Building]]s.{{sfn|Clarke|1985|p=23}} Marble was purchased from the same Italian [[quarry]] that supplied Root's original construction to restore the lobby walls and ceilings.{{sfn|Miller|1991|p=145}}
[[File:Monadnock Building East Facade.jpg|thumb|right|Dearborn Street facade in 2008, showing restored granite entryways, entrances to ground floor shops, and [[fiberglass]] replicas of original [[linen]] window shades]]
The Dearborn Street entrances were reopened and their massive granite [[lintel]]s and surrounds cleared of layers of black paint or replaced. A source was found for the molded bricks needed to repair or replace the curved corners. Large plate glass windows at the entrance were removed and replaced with [[sash window|double-hung window]]s that conformed to the original design.{{sfn|Reuel|1986|p=22}} [[Fiberglass]] shades resembling the original [[linen]] versions were installed to preserve the appearance of the facade.{{sfn|Clarke|1985|p=23}} The average cost of the restoration work was $1 million per floor (${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US|1000000|1989}}}} in {{CURRENTYEAR}} dollars) in 1989, or $47 per square foot ($505.92 per square meter).{{sfn|Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis}}{{sfn|Keohan|1989|p=8}}
Donnell's goal was that the Monadnock would "not only look as it originally did, it [would] also ''live'' as it used to",{{sfn|Miller|1991|p=140}} and he sought tenants for the street-level shops that were similar to their 19th-century occupants.{{sfn|Walsh|1987|p=52}} Shop windows were cleared of all signs and obstructions to preserve intended view from the corridor through to the street. Fluorescent lighting was prohibited and only gold leaf lettering on the glass was permitted for signage. Shops, all individually owned, were selected to fit the architectural character of the building.{{sfn|Walsh|1987|p=52}} A florist, for example, was chosen that evoked a turn-of-the-century atmosphere, as well as a barbershop with vintage fixtures and decor. A [[tobacconist]] with oak furnishings, a pen shop with glass cases, a shoe-shine stand, and other service establishments represented, in Donnell's words, "the kind of small-scale entrepreneurs who occupied those spaces at the turn of the century, the kind of people who bring vitality and life to a building because they have a stake in it."{{sfn|Walsh|1987|p=52}}
[[File:Monadnock Lobby crop.jpg|thumb|left|The retail lobby in 2010, showing faithful restoration of the marble, decorative aluminum, and fixtures and the ambient lighting effect of the [[carbon filament]] bulbs]]
The restoration was a success both critically and commercially. The building was 80&nbsp;percent occupied when bought in 1979 and rented for $5.50 per square foot ($59.20 per square meter). By 1982, it was 91&nbsp;percent occupied and commanded rent of $9 per square foot ($96.89 per square meter).{{sfn|Washburn|1982|p=N_B1}} The Monadnock was selected as one of top restoration projects in the country by the [[National Trust for Historic Preservation]] in 1987, noting "the outstanding quality of the overall restoration effort", and the precision, detail and faithfulness of the interior restoration, in particular the lobby, which "serves as a model for preservation nationwide."{{sfn|''Chicago Tribune''|October 1987|p=2D}}
The restored Monadnock is divided into offices of from {{convert|250|sqft}} to {{convert|6000|sqft}}{{sfn|''Chicago Tribune''|October 1987}}{{sfn|Monadnock Building|2010a}} {{As of|2008}}, it was 98.9&nbsp;percent leased; the 300 tenants are primarily independent professional firms and entrepreneurs.{{sfn|Corfman|2008}}{{sfn|Monadnock Building|2010b}} Rents range from $21 to $23 per square foot ($226 to $247 per square meter), plus electricity.{{sfn|Monadnock Building|2010c}}
The building was offered for sale in 2007, with an expected price of $45 to $60 million.{{sfn|Baeb|Corfman|2007}} A tentative deal was reached at a price of $48 million in 2008.{{sfn|Corfman|2008}}
{{clear}}
== Architecture ==
[[File:Mondanock 1964 Elevation Plan and Section of Typical Bay.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Elevation drawing of typical [[bay window|window bay]]s in the north half. The [[chamfer]]ed brick at the bottom of the window bay is visible in the drawing.]] Together, the two parts of the building have a frontage of {{convert|420|ft}} on Dearborn Street with a depth of {{convert|70|ft}}.{{sfn|Randall|1999|p=185}} The original northern half presents a plain, unbroken vertical mass of purple-brown brick, which is contoured to create a gentle curve at the base of the building and an outward flare to form an austere [[parapet]] at the top.{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|pp=59–60}} The gentle swelling at base and cornice, observed historian Donald Hoffman, "came very close to the bell-shaped column the Egyptians had derived from papyrus".{{sfn|Hoffman|1973|p=174}} The corners of the building are gracefully [[chamfer]]ed as they rise to the top and the oriel windows are chamfered at their base. The floor divisions are not marked on the exterior; the unbroken edifice is interrupted only by a series of [[cantilever]]ed window bays, separated by rows of single thin [[window sill|sill]]ed windows set into the vertical face. The entryways are small, single-height portals topped with plain stone lintels.{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|pp=59–60}}
The south half preserves the lines and color of the older building, but is vertically divided by a [[course (architecture)|stringcourse]] over the second story, emphasizing the building's base, and a large ornamental copper [[cornice]] at the roof line. Massive blocks of red granite, {{convert|6|ft}} thick, frame the large, two-story entrances.{{sfn|Miller|1991|p=147}} The projecting window bays of the original are repeated, but alternate in a pattern of two four-window bays to one recessed strip of windows to create the undulating appearance of the facade that was an early trademark of Holabird & Roche.{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|pp=59–60}}{{sfn|Clarke|Saliga|Zukowsky|1990|pp=42}} Carl Condit, historian of the Chicago school, has commented that:
{{quote | The general appearance of the Monadnock almost belies its masonry construction. The projecting bays of the walls with their large glass areas give the structure a light and open appearance in spite of its great mass.... Stripped of every vestige of ornament, its rigorous geometry softened only by the slight inward curve of the wall at the top of the first story, the outward flare of the parapet, and the progressive rounding of the corners from bottom to top, subtly proportioned and scaled, the Monadnock is a severe yet powerfully expressive composition in horizontal and vertical lines.{{sfn|Condit|1973|p=68}} }}
The Monadnock rests on the [[floating raft system|floating foundation]] system invented by Root for the Montauk Building that revolutionized the way tall buildings were built on Chicago's spongy soil.{{sfn|Miller|1997|p=374}} A {{convert|2|ft|adj=on}} layer of concrete, reinforced with steel beams, forms a [[shallow foundation|spread footing]] extending out {{convert|11|ft}} under the surrounding streets, spreading the weight of the building over a large area of earth.{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=29}} The building was designed to settle {{convert|8|in}}, but by 1905 had settled that much and "several inches more",{{sfn|Randall|1999|p=141}} necessitating reconstruction of the first floor.{{sfn|Weese|1978|p=90}} By 1948, it had settled {{convert|20|in|cm}}, resulting in a step down from the street to the ground floor.{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=29}}{{sfn|Weese|1978|p=89}} The entire east wall is supported on [[caisson (engineering)|caisson]]s sunk to the [[hardpan]], installed when the subway [[Blue Line (Chicago Transit Authority)|Blue Line]] was dug under Dearborn Street in 1940.{{sfn|Randall|1999|p=142}}
[[File:Monadnock Floorplan.JPG|left|thumb|Combined floor plan for north and south halves, showing typical office plans. The closed corridors were opened to connect the two halves as part of the restoration.]]
The narrow building allows an external exposure to all of the 300 offices, which pass natural light via double hung outside windows through feather-chipped glass [[transom (architectural)|transom]]s and hallway partitions into the single central corridor. Skylights bring sunlight into the open stairwells.{{sfn|Keohan|1989|p=2}} The north half corridors are {{convert|20|ft}} wide and the south half corridors are {{convert|11|ft|6|in|m}}. In the north half, there are two open stairs in the center at the one third points, with perforated [[stair riser|riser]]s, white marble treads, and decorative steel railings. There are two banks of four elevators on the west side of the corridor, one for passengers and the other for freight.{{sfn|Weese|1978|p=89}} In the south half, there is a single bank of elevators on the north half of the length. The southern bank was abandoned and slabbed over on each floor.{{sfn|Weese|1978|p=90}} There is a flight of stairs behind each of these shafts with marble treads, closed cast iron risers, and ornamental balusters.{{sfn|Weese|1978|p=89}} The basic office suite is {{convert|600|sqft}}, consisting of one outer office and two or more inner offices.{{sfn|Keohan|1989|p=3}} Heavy internal walls at the quarter and halfway points, the arches of which manifest Root's innovative wind bracing, mark the boundaries of the four original buildings.{{sfn|Weese|1978|p=90}}
{{clear}}
== Surrounding area ==
[[File:Chicago Loop buildings and El station.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Printer's Row]] North Historic District and [[Library–State / Van Buren (CTA)|Library-State/Van Buren]] 'L' station. The Monadnock is at the left, in front of the [[Fisher Building (Chicago)|Fisher Building]] and the red [[CNA Center]]. The [[Old Colony Building (Chicago)|Old Colony Building]] is on the right.]]
The Monadnock belongs to the [[Printing House Row District]], a [[National Historic Landmark]] which includes the Manhattan Building, the [[Old Colony Building (Chicago)|Old Colony Building]], and the [[Fisher Building (Chicago)|Fisher Building]], some of Chicago's seminal [[early skyscrapers]].{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=3}} The Manhattan Building, built by William LeBaron Jenney in 1890, was the first building in Chicago with a complete steel skeleton or "Chicago" construction, an innovation Jenney had introduced in the [[Home Insurance Building]] in 1884.{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=13}} The first 16-story building in America, at the time it was "regarded with awe and fear".{{sfn|Rand McNally|1898|p=80}} Jenney's masterpiece, the Manhattan was considered a technical triumph in construction.{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=9}} The 17-story Old Colony, built by Holabird & Roche in 1894, was considered one of the structural masterpieces of its time for its revolutionary portal form of bracing.{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=16}} It is the only survivor of a group of Chicago school buildings with rounded corner bays.{{sfn|Sinkevitch|2004|p=62}} The [[Fisher Building]], built by Burnham in 1894, was an engineering miracle—the first tall commercial building to be built almost entirely without bricks. Its steel frame and thin terracotta [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain wall]] allowed two-thirds of the surface to be covered with glass.{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=24}}
The district overlaps geographically with the [[Printer's Row]] neighborhood, originally the center of Chicago's printing and publishing industry, but now mostly converted to residential housing.{{sfn|Solomon|2010}} The area is also home to the largest public library in the world, the [[Harold Washington Library]], named for Chicago's first African-American mayor, and the Loop campus of [[Depaul University]], America's largest [[Roman Catholic]] university.{{sfn|Frommers|2009}}{{sfn|''Chicago Tribune''|2010}}
Immediately to the west on Jackson Street is the [[Union League Club of Chicago]], founded in 1879 as a civic organization for "upright, law-abiding businessmen".{{sfn|Union League Club of Chicago|2006}} To the north are the three buildings comprising [[Ludwig Mies Van der Rohe]]'s [[minimalism|minimalist]] [[Federal Plaza]]: the 1964 [[Everett McKinley Dirksen United States Courthouse]], the only courthouse designed by Mies; the 1973 [[United States Post Office Loop Station]]; and the 1975 Kluczynski Federal Building, Mies's last project, considered to mark the apex of his career.{{sfn|O'Gorman|2003|p=27}}{{sfn|Siegel|1970|p=212}} The triangular, 27-story [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, Chicago|Metropolitan Correctional Center]], a detention center serving the Federal courts in the Dirksen Building and nearby [[Ralph H. Metcalfe Federal Building]], is southwest of the Monadnock at Clark and LaSalle.{{sfn|Sinkevitch|2004|pp=74–75}}
The south leg of the [[Chicago Transit Authority]] elevated rail loop runs next to the building on Van Buren Street; the [[Chicago Transit Authority|CTA's]] [[Brown Line (Chicago Transit Authority)|Brown]], [[Orange Line (Chicago Transit Authority)|Orange]], [[Pink Line (Chicago Transit Authority)|Pink]], and [[Purple Line (Chicago Transit Authority)|Purple]] Lines are served by the [[Library–State / Van Buren (CTA)|Library-State/Van Buren]] stop one block to the east. The [[Jackson/Dearborn (CTA)|Jackson]] street subway station, serving the Blue Line, is on the Dearborn Street side of the building.{{sfn|Chicago Transit Authority|2010}}
== Critical reception and historical significance ==
[[File:Monadnock Building South Entrance.jpg|thumb|left|The south entryway, originally the building's main entrance, showing restored granite [[lintel]]s in 2009. The vintage barbershop is to the left.]]
Contemporary Chicago critics considered the building too radical a departure from Burnham & Root's previous designs and too extreme in its stark simplicity and disregard for prevailing aesthetic norms, calling it an "engineer's house"{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1891|p=70}} and a "thoroughly puritanical"{{sfn|Hotchkiss|1891|p=170}} example of commercial style.{{sfn|Bruegmann|1997|p=120}} European critics were even less approving. In the words of French architect Jacques Hermant, "The Monadnock was no longer the result of an artist responding to particular needs with intelligence and drawing from them all of the possible consequences. It is the work of a laborer who, without the slightest study, super-imposes 15 strictly identical stories to make a block then stops when he finds the block high enough."{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=46}}
Other critics saw this lack of style as "natural" and what made the Monadnock truly modern. New York critic Barr Feree wrote in 1892 that "There are no attempts at facades ... no ornamental appendages, nothing but a succession of windows, frankly stating that the structure is an office building, devoted to business, needing and using every available surface."{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=63}} Other critics praised the truthfulness of the building to the ideals of business, which, while "not necessarily the highest to which we might aspire to in art ... are the only ideals the business building ought to express".{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=63}} [[Montgomery Schuyler]], one of the Monadnock's most enthusiastic defenders, argued that the Monadnock's lack of ornament was not a lack of art, but rather "radiated the gravity of modern business life".{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=63}}
[[File:Monadnock Building Vintage Postcard.jpg|thumb|Looking north, from an old [[Curt Teich|Curt Teich & Co.]] postcard]] The Monadnock was widely praised by early twentieth-century German architects, including Mies, who on his arrival in Chicago in 1938 declared that "The Monadnock block is of such vigor and force that I am at once proud and happy to make my home here."{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=136}} These European architects found the building's attention to purpose and functional expression inspiring. [[Bauhaus]] architect [[Ludwig Hilberseimer]] wrote that "The false solution—unfortunately too common—of applying meaningless and misplaced adornment is here instinctively avoided. An innate feeling for proportion gives this great building inner consistency and logical purity."{{sfn|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|p=136}}
Modern critics have praised the Monadnock as one of the most important exemplars of the Chicago school, along with Louis Sullivan's [[Carson, Pirie, Scott and Company Building]].{{sfn|Washburn|1982|p=N_B1}} It has been called "a triumph of unified design"{{sfn|Burchard|Bush-Brown|1967|p=251}} comparable to [[Henry Hobson Richardson]]'s [[Marshall Field's Wholesale Store]], and "one of the most exciting aesthetic experiences our commercial architecture has ever produced".{{sfn|Condit|1973|p=69}}
The building was one of the first five selected by the Chicago Commission on Architectural Landmarks in 1958, "in recognition of its original design and its historical interest as the highest wall-bearing structure in Chicago".{{sfn|Overby|Homolka|1963|p=2}}{{sfn|''Chicago Daily Tribune''|May 1958|p=B6}} The commission went on to note that the "restrained use of brick, soaring massive walls, omission of ornamental forms, unite in a building simple yet majestic."{{sfn|Overby|Homolka|1963|p=2}} In 1973, the Chicago City Council voted unanimously to designate the Monadnock a [[Chicago Landmark]], stating that "The two halves of this building provide a unique perspective for examining the history and development of modern architecture.... Together, they mark the end of one building tradition and the beginning of another."{{sfn|City of Chicago|1973}}{{sfn|Ziemba|1973|p=W4}}{{efn|name=i}} Critics of the Monadnock's landmark status objected that it would prevent the necessary demolition of the building, which was "an excellent example of a building that is ... no longer fulfilling the functions it was designed to fulfill" and "a wasting asset" that underperformed the market and was far less valuable than the land on which it stood would be.{{sfn|Washburn|1974|p=B1}}
The [[National Register of Historic Places]], to which the Monadnock was added in 1970, noted that "the sheer, unadorned walls of this building forming a powerful mass became, prophetically, a forerunner of the 'slab skyscraper'—a style not popular until the late 1920s" and that "the two sections ... make, as an ensemble, one of the strongest, yet refined architectural statements in the development of twentieth century architecture."{{sfn|National Park Service|1970}}{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=8}} Its nomination as a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1976, as part of the [[South Dearborn Street – Printing House Row Historic District]], included the comment that it was "one of the most classical statements ever made in the skyscraper idiom."{{sfn|Pitts|1976|p=29}}
== Notes ==
{{notes | notes =
{{efn | name = a | The other was [[William E. Hale]], who introduced the hydraulic elevator to Chicago in 1878. {{harv|Miller|1997|p=311}} }}
{{efn | name = b | When completed, at 215 feet (66 m), the Monadnock was the tallest commercial masonry building in the world and, {{as of|2000|lc=y}}, it remained so. {{harv|Wiseman|2000|p=56}} The tallest of its type, it is not, however, the tallest masonry building to be found, a distinction that belongs to the stone and marble [[Philadelphia City Hall]], at 541 feet (167 m). {{harv|Priwer|Phillips|2009|p=51}} }}
{{efn | name = c | The Monadnock used a portal-[[strut]] system, which braced the masonry piers with iron [[girder]]s. This evolved into what would come to be known as the portal system, using solid web plates instead, first used by Holabird & Roche in the Old Colony Building in 1894. {{harv|Freitag|1895|pp=151–152}} }}
{{efn | name = d | Feather chipping creates a frosted texture on plate glass using a technique called glue chipping, in which the glass is sandblasted to roughen the surface and then painted with animal hide glue which is fan dried at a carefully controlled temperature to shrink the glue, creating a surface of feather-like chips in the glass. }}
{{efn | name = e | The [[Washington Monument]] was fitted with a {{convert|100|oz|kg|adj=on}} cast aluminum cap in 1884, arguably the first architectural use of aluminum. The Monadnock represents the first use of aluminum as a functional element of building construction. {{harv|National Park Service|1992|p=84}} }}
{{efn | name = f | The Monadnock had two (and later four) names because it was legally four separate buildings—the Monadnock, the Kearsage, the Katahdin, and the Wachusett—each owned by a different branch of the Brooks family that could sell their share independently. The other names were abandoned in the late 1890s and the four-way ownership was dissolved in the early 1920s. The letters M, K, and W can still be found on the original cast iron doorknobs, indicating which building each office originally was in. {{harv|Merwood-Salisbury|2009|pp=159–160}} }}
{{efn | name = g | Holabird & Roche moved their offices to the north half of the Monadnock in 1892, while the south half was under construction. They remained there until 1910, and built no fewer than five major projects for the Brooks brothers, practically at the same time, all within blocks of the Monadnock. {{harv|Bruegmann|1997|pp=38,40}} }}
{{efn | name = h | The Van Buren street side was designed to be the main entrance. When the 'L' tracks were erected literally on the doorstep of the building, the configuration was reversed to make Jackson street the building's "front". {{harv|Fuller|1958|p=B5}} }}
{{efn | name = i | The original Commission on Architectural Landmarks was advisory in nature and was ultimately unsuccessful in protecting Chicago's landmark buildings. Beginning in 1968, Chicago Landmark status was granted by [[statute]], which prohibited the destruction or drastic alteration of designated buildings without approval from the city. {{harv|''Chicago Tribune''|1968|p=B10}} }}
